International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu, 25 Sep 2003
From: Fabrice Simon, MD <simon-f@wanadoo.fr>

The epidemic of [a disease whose symptoms include] abnormal movements
among children of the same area in Sudan is rather surprising. It
seems to be different from classical diseases. Of course, I agree
with colleagues saying that autopsies including a wide-spectrum
search for microbiological or toxic agents would be useful to solve
this mystery.
I would suggest including tests for Whipple's disease, although no
epidemic has been reported previously, to my knowledge. Infection due
to _Tropheryma whippleii_ is soil-transmitted. It can produce
malabsorption, leading to severe impairment to the physical
development of children. In late stages, after years of evolution,
this disease strikes the central nervous system with dementia and
abnormal motions distinct from seizures. Classically, there is no
real meningitis, only a subacute or chronic encephalitis.
It would be of interest to know how the children responded to
antibiotics, such as cotrimoxazole, or even ceftriaxone (if available
locally), which is much more efficient on neuro-Whipple. Hoping that
these ideas could help these unfortunate Sudanese children.
--
Fabrice Simon, MD
Tropical Medicine Institute for the French Army
Parc du Pharo, BP 46
13998 Marseille Armees
France
<simon-f@wanadoo.fr>
