[2]
Date: Thu, 25 Sep 2003
From: Gerry Bryant <Gerry.Bryant@lnrhpt.nhs.uk>

When I heard this story, I was reminded of the strange disease known
as Kuru (shivering) that affected mainly children in the Fore tribe
in Papua New Guinea. Has a transmissible spongiform encephalopathy
been positively ruled out as the cause of this disease?
There is a reference to monkey flesh. Do they eat monkey (meat,
offal, brain)? Monkeys can certainly be infected with TSEs.
Anthropological techniques were invaluable in investigating the cause
of Kuru -- can such techniques help here?
--
Gerry Bryant, Consultant
East Midlands (South) Health Protection Team
Gwendolen House, Gwendolen Road,
Leicester LE5 4QF UK
Phone: 0116 295 2195/2196
Fax: 0116 295 2190
<gerry.bryant@lnrhpt.nhs.uk>
[We thank Dr. Fabrice Simon and Dr. Gerry Bryant for their comments.
Though nothing should be ruled out at this stage, Whipple's disease
in children would be unusual. Treatment with
trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole is recommended for a year, and a
treatment trial without a more certain diagnosis seems unfeasible.
As alluded to in the comments contained in the previous post, a prion
disease like Kuru or Creutzfeldt-Jakob is a possibility, but such
diseases in humans have a much more rapid course than the prolonged
disease described in the report. A novel prion disease transmitted
from bush meat is a possibility, but we would expect to see cases in
adults as well. Autopsies would tell us whether changes were
compatible with other known prion diseases. - Mod.EP]
